The interdiction of prodigals had been a matter of customary law even before tbe XII Tables, Dig. 27. 10. 1. pr. The prodigus was subjeeted to cura on an application to that effect being made to the praetor by his near relations: the form of interdiction is given by Paulus, sent. rec. 3. 4 a and 7 ‘moribus per praetorem bonis interdicitur hoc modo: quando tua bona patema avitaque nequitia tua disperdis liberosque tuos ad eges· tatem perducis, ob eam rem tibi ea re commercioque interdico' Under the early law the office belonged to the agnatos only if the prodigus had succeeded his father ab intestato, Ulpian, reg. 12. 3.
